<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="97" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="97">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sacc., Michelia 2: 264" authorityYear="1881" baseAuthorityName="Pers." class="Sordariomycetes" family="Valsaceae" genus="Cytospora" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Cytospora leucostoma" order="Diaporthales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="leucostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Cytospora leucostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is commonly associated with canker disease of 
<taxonomicName genus="Prunoideae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="genus">Prunoideae</taxonomicName>
of 
<taxonomicName family="Rosaceae" genus="Prunoideae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
in China (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Persoonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B8" refString="Fan, XL, Bezerra, JDP, Tian, CM, Crous, PW, 2020. Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China. Persoonia 45: 1 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" title="Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China." url="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" volume="45" year="2020">Fan et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Morphologically, our taxa are similar to previous descriptions of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. leucostoma" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="species" species="leucostoma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">C. leucostoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having multi-loculate pycnidial stromata with a conspicuous black conceptacle, producing elongate-allantoid, large conidia (4.5-6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Teng, SC" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Biology and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" refId="B43" refString="Teng, SC, 1963. Fungi of China. Science Press. Beijing, China." title="Fungi of China. Science Press. Beijing, China." year="1963">Teng 1963</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zhuang, WY" journalOrPublisher="Mycobiology" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" refId="B53" refString="Zhuang, WY, 2005. Fungi of Northwestern China. Mycotaxon, Ltd. New York, USA." title="Fungi of Northwestern China. Mycotaxon, Ltd. New York, USA." year="2005">Zhuang 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Persoonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B8" refString="Fan, XL, Bezerra, JDP, Tian, CM, Crous, PW, 2020. Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China. Persoonia 45: 1 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" title="Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China." url="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" volume="45" year="2020">Fan et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). The greenish-yellow of the cultures on PDA medium from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Juglandaceae" genus="Juglans" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Juglans mandshurica" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mandshurica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Juglans mandshurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to descriptions of those collected from 
<taxonomicName genus="Prunoideae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" rank="genus">Prunoideae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" author="Fan, XL" journalOrPublisher="Persoonia" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" pagination="1 - 45" refId="B8" refString="Fan, XL, Bezerra, JDP, Tian, CM, Crous, PW, 2020. Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China. Persoonia 45: 1 - 45, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" title="Cytospora (Diaporthales) in China." url="https://doi.org/10.3767/persoonia.2020.45.01" volume="45" year="2020">Fan et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Multigene phylogenetic analyses supported the morphological results with high support values (ML/MP/BI = 100/100/1, Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 2. Phylogram of Cytospora, based on combined ITS, LSU, act, rpb 2, tef 1 - α and tub 2 genes. The MP and ML bootstrap support values above 50 % are shown at the first and second positions, respectively. Thickened branches represent posterior probabilities above 0.95 from the BI. Ex-type strains are in bold. Strains from the current study are in blue." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.62.47854.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/375794" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">2</figureCitation>
). By combining morphology and the DNA data, our isolates collected from dead branches of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Prunus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Prunus sibirica" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sibirica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Prunus sibirica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Juglandaceae" genus="Juglans" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Juglans mandshurica" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="97" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mandshurica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="97">Juglans mandshurica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
